<section xml:id="sec-derivApp-related" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Related Rates</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Set up a related rates problem by identifying variables, constants, current values, and known rates.</li>
      <li>Write a geometric relationship among variables, then differentiate with respect to time using the Chain Rule.</li>
      <li>Compute an unknown rate at a specific instant by substituting current values only at the end.</li>
      <li>Check answers for sign and real-world plausibility, including unit consistency.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="pulley-example">
    <title>Pulley Example</title>

    <p>
      Consider a weight hanging from a rope that goes up to a pulley 10 ft above the floor and then down to your hand,
      which is 3 ft above the floor and 15 ft horizontally from the pulley. If you walk away from the pulley at
      <m>2</m> ft/sec, how fast will the weight rise?
    </p>

    <p>
      This is a <term>related rates</term> problem: we want an unknown rate of change from a known rate, using a geometric relationship.
      Start by drawing a picture and labeling constants and variables. Let <m>h(t)</m> be the horizontal distance from the weight to your hand,
      and let <m>r(t)</m> be the length of the rope segment from the pulley to your hand.
      The problem gives the current value <m>h(0)=15</m> and the current rate <m>h'(0)=2</m> (ft/sec). We want <m>r'(0)</m>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-pulley">
      <caption>Pulley setup with variables <m>h(t)</m> and <m>r(t)</m>.</caption>
      <image source="2-8-Pulley.png" width="75%"/>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The vertical distance from your hand up to the pulley is constant: <m>10-3=7</m> ft. By the Pythagorean Theorem,
      the geometry implies
      <me>
        r(t)^2=h(t)^2+7^2=h(t)^2+49.
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      One approach is to solve for <m>r(t)</m> and then differentiate.
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle r(t) 
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \sqrt{h(t)^2+49}
\\[0.9em]
\displaystyle r'(t)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{1}{2}(h(t)^2+49)^{-1/2}\cdot \left(h(t)^2+49\right)'
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{1}{2}(h(t)^2+49)^{-1/2}\cdot 2h(t)h'(t)
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{h(t)h'(t)}{\sqrt{h(t)^2+49}}.
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Now substitute the current values:
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle r'(0)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{h(0)\,h'(0)}{\sqrt{h(0)^2+49}}
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{(15)(2)}{\sqrt{15^2+49}}
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{30}{\sqrt{274}}
\approx 1.8\ \text{ft/sec}.
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      The weight rises at the same rate that the rope segment <m>r(t)</m> increases, so the weight rises at about
      <m>1.8</m> ft/sec at that instant.
    </p>

    <remark xml:id="rem-plug-in-last">
      <p>
        Plug in the current values only at the <emph>last</emph> step. If you substitute before differentiating,
        you turn variables into constants and their derivatives become zero.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <p>
      We can also do this more directly by implicitly differentiating the relationship <m>r(t)^2=h(t)^2+49</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \left(r(t)^2\right)'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \left(h(t)^2+49\right)'
\\[0.9em]
\displaystyle 2r(t)r'(t)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 2h(t)h'(t)
\\[0.9em]
\displaystyle r'(t)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{h(t)h'(t)}{r(t)}.
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>r(0)=\sqrt{h(0)^2+49}=\sqrt{274}</m>, this gives the same numerical result as above.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="method-related-rates">
    <title>A Method for Related Rates Problems</title>

    <ol>
      <li>
        Draw a picture labeled with:
        <ul>
          <li>numerical constant values,</li>
          <li>letter variables and their current values,</li>
          <li>arrows showing known current rates (derivatives),</li>
          <li>an arrow for the unknown target rate you want.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        Write an equation relating the variables using geometry (or a known formula).
      </li>
      <li>
        Assume each variable depends on time <m>t</m>, then differentiate both sides with respect to <m>t</m>.
        Use the Chain Rule whenever a variable appears inside a power, root, trig function, etc.
        Solve for the target derivative if needed.
      </li>
      <li>
        Substitute the current values and current rates to compute the target rate.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="spill-radius-example">
    <title>Spill Radius Example</title>

    <p>
      A stream of water spreads a circular puddle on the floor. If the puddle is 1 meter across and the stream increases the area at a rate of
      <m>2</m> m<sup>2</sup>/min, how quickly is the puddle widening at that instant?
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-puddle">
      <caption>A growing circular puddle with radius <m>r(t)</m> and area <m>A(t)</m>.</caption>
      <image source="2-8-Puddle.png" width="55%"/>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Let <m>r(t)</m> be the puddleâ€™s radius and <m>A(t)</m> its area. A diameter of 1 m means the current radius is
      <m>r(0)=\frac12</m>. The given rate is <m>A'(0)=2</m> m<sup>2</sup>/min. We want <m>r'(0)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The geometric relationship is
      <me>
        A(t)=\pi r(t)^2.
      </me>
      Differentiate both sides with respect to time:
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle A'(t)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \pi\left(r(t)^2\right)'
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 2\pi r(t)r'(t).
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve for the target rate and substitute the current values:
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle r'(t)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{A'(t)}{2\pi r(t)}
\\[0.9em]
\displaystyle r'(0)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{A'(0)}{2\pi r(0)}
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{2}{2\pi(\frac12)}
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{2}{\pi}
\approx 0.64\ \text{m/min}.
\end{array}
    </me>

    <remark xml:id="rem-puddle-plausible">
      <p>
        Always check plausibility. A radius increase of about 0.6 m per minute can be reasonable, depending on flow rate and surface.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="searchlight-example">
    <title>Searchlight Example</title>

    <p>
      A searchlight shines along a wall 20 meters away. If the light is currently <m>30^\circ</m> away from pointing directly at the wall
      and the light is rotating at <m>5^\circ</m> per second, what is the speed of the bright spot moving along the wall at that instant?
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-searchlight">
      <caption>The spotlight position <m>s(t)</m> depends on the angle <m>\theta(t)</m>.</caption>
      <image source="2-8-Searchlight.png" width="55%"/>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Let <m>\theta(t)</m> be the angle and <m>s(t)</m> the distance of the spot from the point on the wall closest to the light.
      The geometry gives
      <me>
        \tan(\theta(t))=\frac{s(t)}{20},
      </me>
      so
      <me>
        s(t)=20\tan(\theta(t)).
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      Differentiate with respect to time:
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle s'(t)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 20\left(\tan(\theta(t))\right)'\,\theta'(t)
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 20\sec^2(\theta(t))\,\theta'(t).
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Trig derivatives require radians. Convert the current angle and angular speed:
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \theta(0)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 30^\circ
\ =\ 30\left(\frac{2\pi}{360}\right)
\ =\ \frac{\pi}{6}\ \text{rad},
\\[1.0em]
\displaystyle \theta'(0)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 5^\circ/\text{sec}
\ =\ 5\left(\frac{2\pi}{360}\right)
\ =\ \frac{\pi}{36}\ \text{rad/sec}.
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Now compute:
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle s'(0)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 20\sec^2\!\left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right)\cdot \frac{\pi}{36}.
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>\cos(\pi/6)=\sqrt{3}/2</m>, we have <m>\sec^2(\pi/6)=\left(\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^2=\frac{4}{3}</m>, so
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle s'(0)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 20\cdot \frac{4}{3}\cdot \frac{\pi}{36}
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{20\pi}{27}
\approx 2.3\ \text{m/sec}.
\end{array}
    </me>

    <remark xml:id="rem-sign-speed">
      <p>
        The problem asks for <emph>speed</emph>, so report <m>|s'(0)|</m>. If the rotation direction were opposite,
        the derivative would change sign but the speed would be the same.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <remark xml:id="rem-radians-required">
      <p>
        If you mistakenly use <m>\theta'(0)=5</m> in degrees/sec inside the derivative formula, the numerical answer will be wrong.
        Convert to radians/sec before substituting.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="flashlight-examples">
    <title>Flashlight Examples</title>

    <p>
      A flashlight shines a cone of light straight toward a wall. The lit region on the wall is a circle.
      What is the rate of change of the lit circular area if:
      (a) the flashlight moves toward the wall at 2 m/sec; (b) the flashlight stays 5 m from the wall, but the focus narrows so the total angle decreases at
      <m>10^\circ</m> per second?
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="flashlight-a">
      <title>Case (a): Moving Toward the Wall</title>

      <figure xml:id="fig-flashlight-a">
        <caption>As the flashlight moves, similar triangles relate the radius to the distance <m>\ell(t)</m>.</caption>
        <image source="2-8-Flashlight-2.png" width="88%"/>
      </figure>

      <p>
        Let <m>\ell(t)</m> be the distance from the wall, <m>r(t)</m> the radius of the lit circle, and <m>A(t)</m> its area.
        We are given <m>\ell(0)=5</m>, <m>\ell'(0)=-2</m>, and <m>r(0)=\frac12</m>.
        Similar triangles show <m>\frac{r(t)}{\ell(t)}=\frac{1/2}{5}=\frac{1}{10}</m>, so
        <m>r(t)=\frac{1}{10}\ell(t)</m>, and therefore
        <m>A(t)=\pi r(t)^2=\frac{\pi}{100}\ell(t)^2</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Differentiate and substitute:
      </p>

      <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle A'(t)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{\pi}{100}\left(\ell(t)^2\right)'
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{\pi}{50}\ell(t)\,\ell'(t),
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle A'(0)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{\pi}{50}\ell(0)\,\ell'(0)
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{\pi}{50}(5)(-2)
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle -\frac{\pi}{5}\ \text{m}^2/\text{s}
\approx -0.63\ \text{m}^2/\text{s}.
\end{array}
      </me>

      <p>
        The negative sign matches the situation: as the flashlight moves closer, the circle on the wall shrinks.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="flashlight-b">
      <title>Case (b): Narrowing the Beam</title>

      <p>
        Now the distance is constant at 5 m, but the beam angle changes. Let <m>\theta(t)</m> be the total cone angle and
        let <m>r(t)</m> be the radius of the lit circle.
        The right triangle in the diagram uses the half-angle <m>\theta(t)/2</m>:
      </p>

      <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \tan\!\left(\frac{\theta(t)}{2}\right)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{r(t)}{5},
\\[0.9em]
\displaystyle r(t)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 5\tan\!\left(\frac{\theta(t)}{2}\right),
\\[0.9em]
\displaystyle A(t)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \pi r(t)^2
\ =\ 25\pi \tan^2\!\left(\frac{\theta(t)}{2}\right).
\end{array}
      </me>

      <p>
        Differentiate using the Chain Rule:
      </p>

      <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle A'(t)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 25\pi \left(\tan^2\!\left(\frac{\theta(t)}{2}\right)\right)'
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 50\pi \tan\!\left(\frac{\theta(t)}{2}\right)\left(\tan\!\left(\frac{\theta(t)}{2}\right)\right)'\cdot \left(\frac{\theta(t)}{2}\right)'
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 50\pi \tan\!\left(\frac{\theta(t)}{2}\right)\sec^2\!\left(\frac{\theta(t)}{2}\right)\cdot \frac{\theta'(t)}{2}.
\end{array}
      </me>

      <p>
        We are given <m>\theta'(0)=-10^\circ/\text{sec}</m>, so <m>\theta'(0)/2=-5^\circ/\text{sec}</m>.
        Convert to radians/sec:
        <m>\displaystyle \frac{\theta'(0)}{2}=-5\left(\frac{2\pi}{360}\right)=-\frac{\pi}{36}</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        We are not given <m>\theta(0)</m>, but we are given <m>r(0)=\frac12</m> and distance 5 m, so
        <m>\tan(\theta(0)/2)=\frac{(1/2)}{5}=\frac{1}{10}</m>.
        Also, using the same right triangle, the adjacent side is 5 and the opposite side is <m>1/2</m>,
        so the hypotenuse squared is <m>5^2+(1/2)^2=25+\frac14=\frac{101}{4}</m>, giving
        <m>\sec^2(\theta(0)/2)=\frac{\text{hyp}^2}{\text{adj}^2}=\frac{101/4}{25}=\frac{101}{100}</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Substitute into the derivative formula:
      </p>

      <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle A'(0)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 50\pi\left(\frac{1}{10}\right)\left(\frac{101}{100}\right)\left(-\frac{\pi}{36}\right)
\\[0.9em]
\amp=\amp \displaystyle -\frac{101}{720}\pi^2
\approx -1.38\ \text{m}^2/\text{s}.
\end{array}
      </me>

      <p>
        The sign makes sense: the beam narrows, so the lit area decreases.
      </p>

      <remark xml:id="rem-angle-size-check">
        <p>
          A quick check: <m>\theta(0)=2\arctan(1/10)\approx 11^\circ</m>. If the angle is decreasing at about
          <m>10^\circ</m>/sec, the circle can shrink very quickly at that instant, so a relatively large negative
          area rate is plausible.
        </p>
      </remark>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="practice-related-rates">
    <title>Practice Problems</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-rr-1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          In the pulley example, explain why substituting <m>h(0)=15</m> into <m>r(t)^2=h(t)^2+49</m> before differentiating
          leads to an incorrect conclusion about <m>r'(0)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-rr-2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A circular disk has radius <m>r(t)</m> and area <m>A(t)=\pi r(t)^2</m>. If <m>r'(t)</m> is constant and positive,
          describe how the sign and size of <m>A'(t)</m> change as <m>r(t)</m> grows.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-rr-3">
      <statement>
        <p>
          In the searchlight example, identify which step requires converting degrees to radians, and explain why that conversion is essential.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
</section>
